{{Infobox officeholder | image = | name =Robert Malval | imagesize = | caption = | order =[[List of Prime Ministers of Haiti|5th]] [[Prime Minister of Haiti]] | office = | term_start =August 30, 1993 | term_end =November 8, 1994 | president =[[Émile Jonassaint]] (provisional) | predecessor =[[Marc Bazin]] | successor =[[Smarck Michel]] | birth_date = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1943|7|11}} | birth_place =[[Port-au-Prince]], [[Haiti]] | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = Haitian | party = | spouse = Linda Frisch | relations = | children = 3 | residence = | alma_mater = [[University of Miami]]<ref>Pezzullo 2011</ref> | occupation = Businessman | profession = | signature = | website = | footnotes = }}
'''Robert Malval''' (born July 11, 1943 in [[Port-au-Prince]]) was the prime minister of [[Haiti]] from August 30, 1993 to November 8, 1994.
An industrialist and business leader of [[Lebanon|Lebanese]] descent,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1993-08-31/news/9308300655_1_robert-malval-haitian-embassy-president-jean-bertrand-aristide |title=New Top Minister Vows He Will End Haiti's `Madness' |accessdate=30 January 2014}}</ref> Malval was appointed on August 16, 1993 by the President-in-exile, [[Jean-Bertrand Aristide]], who gave Malval the task of reconciling the feuding parties.<ref>[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/60371007.html?dids=60371007:60371007&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Sep+01%2C+1993&author=KENNETH+FREED&pub=Los+Angeles+Times+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&desc=Military+Poses+Obstacle+to+Haiti+Stability+Caribbean%3A+Malval+faces+daunting+task+on+reforms.+U.N.%2C+U.S.+aides+arrive+to+lend+support.&pqatl=google ''Los Angeles Times'', September 1, 1993, cited at pqarchiver]</ref> He defied the Army-backed president, [[Émile Jonassaint]].<ref>[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/72245487.html?dids=72245487:72245487&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=May+17%2C+1994&author=&pub=The+Washington+Post+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&desc=Haitian+Premier+Rebels%2C+And+Promptly+Loses+Post&pqatl=google ''Washington Post'', May 17, 1994, cited at pqarchiver]</ref> In December 1993, he resigned his post and criticized Aristide as an "erratic" figure who was hampering efforts to solve the political crisis.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1993/12/20/world/premier-of-haiti-criticizes-aristide.html ''New York Times'', December 20, 1993]</ref>
His predecessor was [[Marc Bazin]]; his successor was [[Smarck Michel]].
